WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.285 --> 00:00:05.900
Welcome to the DietDoctor podcast
with Dr. Bret Scher.

00:00:05.900 --> 00:00:08.980
Today is my pleasure to be joined
by Dr. Robert Lustig.

00:00:08.980 --> 00:00:15.140
Dr. Lustig is a pediatric endocrinologist
recently retired from clinical practice at UCSF

00:00:15.140 --> 00:00:17.699
but still very active in research

00:00:17.699 --> 00:00:22.980
and now even having gone to get
a Masters of law from the Hastings College

00:00:22.980 --> 00:00:27.019
so that he can get more involved
into the public policy side of things.

00:00:27.019 --> 00:00:31.100
Because his whole life
he's been fighting childhood obesity

00:00:31.100 --> 00:00:35.659
and he's been studying the CNS regulation
of energy balance.

00:00:35.659 --> 00:00:39.460
But he knows it's more than science
that is affecting this

00:00:39.460 --> 00:00:41.979
because this is blown up
in front of his eyes.

00:00:41.979 --> 00:00:46.899
He has seen this epidemic of obesity and
diabetes take place as he's been practicing.

00:00:46.899 --> 00:00:50.060
And he's realized that it's going to take
more than science;

00:00:50.060 --> 00:00:53.979
it's going to take public policy to halt this
and reverse it.

00:00:53.979 --> 00:00:56.500
And that's what makes it
such an interesting discussion,

00:00:56.500 --> 00:01:00.100
he has such a great depth of knowledge
of the history of public policies,

00:01:00.100 --> 00:01:06.099
of analogous scenarios of public policy
and how we can use that information

00:01:06.099 --> 00:01:10.340
to try and help us stem this this epidemic
that we're in the middle of

00:01:10.340 --> 00:01:14.180
and what can we define
as the possible causes:

00:01:14.180 --> 00:01:17.700
fructose, glucose, sucrose, sugar,

00:01:17.700 --> 00:01:20.540
all these terms get thrown around
as if they were one thing.

00:01:20.540 --> 00:01:23.939
We'll we talk a little bit about that
to identify the specifics of it

00:01:23.939 --> 00:01:28.379
and also just the processed food
and how that plays into it as well,

00:01:28.379 --> 00:01:31.500
the so-called healthy natural fruit juices.

00:01:31.500 --> 00:01:33.980
So I really enjoyed this discussion
with Robert

00:01:33.980 --> 00:01:39.939
because he has such a great grasp
on both the science and the public policy

00:01:39.939 --> 00:01:45.099
and how to help us draw a roadmap
on how to get out of this and reverse it.

00:01:45.099 --> 00:01:47.780
So I really hope you'll enjoy this discussion

00:01:47.780 --> 00:01:51.459
and in the end he'll list the different ways
to get in touch with him.

00:01:51.459 --> 00:01:55.700
He's involved in for-profits and nonprofits,
he's written a number of books,

00:01:55.700 --> 00:01:59.540
so definitely stay tuned to the end so you
can learn all the things he's involved in

00:01:59.540 --> 00:02:01.579
and if you want to hear more

00:02:01.579 --> 00:02:04.219
because there's a lot more that
he has to say and has produced

00:02:04.219 --> 00:02:07.500
that is very worthwhile
to read and listen to.

00:02:07.500 --> 00:02:10.092
So enjoy this interview
with Dr. Robert Lustig.

00:02:14.841 --> 00:02:18.618
Dr. Lustig thank you so much for joining me
on the DietDoctor podcast today.

00:02:18.714 --> 00:02:20.251
My pleasure,
but it's Rob to you.

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:22.419
Rob, you got it, thank you.

00:02:22.419 --> 00:02:27.340
Now in your career you have seen
this epidemic rise in front of your face

00:02:27.340 --> 00:02:29.580
as a pediatric endocrinologist.

00:02:29.580 --> 00:02:31.699
I mean it's one thing,
I've said this before,

00:02:31.699 --> 00:02:34.180
it's one thing for me to see diabetes
in adults

00:02:34.180 --> 00:02:37.500
and the consequences that happen
in their 50s, 60s and 70s.

00:02:37.500 --> 00:02:41.259
But to see it in a pediatric population
with type 2 diabetes

00:02:41.259 --> 00:02:44.379
and now nonalcoholic fatty liver disease,

00:02:44.379 --> 00:02:48.740
I mean this must be heartbreaking to see
in kids and you've seen it just exploding.

00:02:48.961 --> 00:02:53.259
Yeah, I mean I went into pediatrics
to stay away from chronic disease

00:02:53.259 --> 00:02:55.699
and now that's all I do.

00:02:55.699 --> 00:02:59.180
I went into pediatric endocrinology
to take care of short kids

00:02:59.180 --> 00:03:01.340
and they got fat on me.

00:03:01.340 --> 00:03:04.620
They grew horizontally
rather than vertically.

00:03:04.620 --> 00:03:07.180
And that happened on my watch.

00:03:07.180 --> 00:03:09.860
And, you know, they're coming in

00:03:09.860 --> 00:03:13.659
and for every patient I take care of,
10 more show up on the doorstep.

00:03:13.659 --> 00:03:15.860
Something is wrong.

00:03:15.860 --> 00:03:19.180
And of course everybody knows
that something's wrong,

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:23.500
but everyone seems to have
a different answer for what's wrong

00:03:23.500 --> 00:03:25.497
and we can't tie it together.

00:03:25.719 --> 00:03:28.539
And that's what has really halted
any progress.

00:03:28.539 --> 00:03:33.060
All these different voices, different theories,
without a unifying approach

00:03:33.060 --> 00:03:36.505
has just really made it
so we can't make any progress.

00:03:36.599 --> 00:03:40.500
Plus unfortunately some
of the stakeholders in this discussion

00:03:40.500 --> 00:03:42.900
have money associated with it.

00:03:42.900 --> 00:03:47.699
So there are dark forces actually
trying to maintain the status quo.

00:03:47.839 --> 00:03:49.820
Tell me some more about that.

00:03:49.900 --> 00:03:52.139
We can go on for hours

00:03:52.139 --> 00:03:55.539
but the fact of the matter is that
the food industry has a vested interest

00:03:55.539 --> 00:03:59.533
and have pulled out all the stops
in the same way that tobacco did.

00:03:59.534 --> 00:04:05.180
Marion Nestle just released this week
a book called &lt;i&gt;Unsavory Truth.&lt;/i&gt;

00:04:05.180 --> 00:04:08.539
My colleagues, Aseem Malhotra
and Grant Schofield and I

00:04:08.539 --> 00:04:12.819
published an article earlier this year
that the science against sugar alone

00:04:12.819 --> 00:04:16.899
is not enough to win the battle
against obesity and type 2 diabetes.

00:04:16.899 --> 00:04:21.180
Opposition from vested interests
must be taken first.

00:04:21.180 --> 00:04:25.139
So we know who's on the other side.

00:04:25.139 --> 00:04:28.620
And the problem is that the other side
has a very large mouthpiece

00:04:28.620 --> 00:04:30.697
and a whole bunch of money.

00:04:30.793 --> 00:04:35.740
Right, a lot more money than scientists
and universities and physicians,

00:04:35.740 --> 00:04:40.654
certainly as individuals and even trying
to group together can't come close.

00:04:40.740 --> 00:04:43.139
So we're doing our best.

00:04:43.139 --> 00:04:47.579
The good news is we've got the science
and the science is very potent,

00:04:47.579 --> 00:04:51.060
but, you know,
not everyone's a scientist.

00:04:51.060 --> 00:04:53.540
Sometimes not even scientists
are scientists.

00:04:53.609 --> 00:04:59.221
Your own record is basically saying that
fructose is probably the number one concern.

00:04:59.443 --> 00:05:04.396
I'm not going to say that,
I won't say it's the number one concern.

00:05:04.397 --> 00:05:08.060
Trans fats used to be
the number one concern.

00:05:08.060 --> 00:05:13.139
But we figured that out, it took 25 years
to figure it out and finally get rid of it.

00:05:13.359 --> 00:05:15.996
Which shows how slow
the needle moves on these.

00:05:16.061 --> 00:05:19.026
Well because there were dark forces
there as well.

00:05:19.027 --> 00:05:28.939
Now I think that sugar is not the cause
of obesity, diabetes, fatty liver disease etc.

00:05:28.939 --> 00:05:33.980
but it's the most malleable,
is the one that is the low hanging fruit,

00:05:33.980 --> 00:05:40.579
it is the one that's added to other foods
specifically for the food industry's purposes,

00:05:40.579 --> 00:05:47.540
therefore it is the easiest one
to attack and target upfront.

00:05:47.756 --> 00:05:50.740
Now do you think it's most important
to target sugar

00:05:50.740 --> 00:05:56.710
or to differentiate it between fructose,
glucose, sucrose and sort of break it down?

00:05:56.819 --> 00:05:59.420
To be honest with you,
they're the same thing.

00:05:59.420 --> 00:06:04.899
Once you understand what these different
chemicals do in the body

00:06:04.899 --> 00:06:09.339
that is glucose and fructose,
they are not the same,

00:06:09.339 --> 00:06:16.699
the food industry will tell you
11 ways from Sunday, a sugar is a sugar.

00:06:16.699 --> 00:06:23.540
It is absolutely completely fallacious
and it's disingenuous to boot.

00:06:23.540 --> 00:06:27.339
They are not handled the same,
glucose and fructose.

00:06:27.339 --> 00:06:33.180
As it turns out sucrose, high fructose
corn syrup, agave, maple syrup, honey,

00:06:33.180 --> 00:06:38.459
are all basically equivalent,
they're all half glucose, half fructose.

00:06:38.459 --> 00:06:43.180
Now glucose is the energy of life, every cell
on the planet burns glucose for energy.

00:06:43.180 --> 00:06:46.860
Glucose is so important that if you
don't consume it, your body makes it.

00:06:46.860 --> 00:06:50.420
And we know that because the Inuit
who ate whale blubber,

00:06:50.420 --> 00:06:56.500
who didn't ever see a piece of bread
or grow a strand of wheat

00:06:56.500 --> 00:06:59.019
still had a serum  glucose level.

00:06:59.019 --> 00:07:03.100
Vilhjalmur Stefansson and his assistant,
the famous Arctic explorer,

00:07:03.100 --> 00:07:06.339
checked himself into Bellevue in 1928

00:07:06.339 --> 00:07:11.180
and they ate nothing but meat for one year
on their clinical research Center.

00:07:11.180 --> 00:07:13.060
They still had a serum glucose level

00:07:13.060 --> 00:07:15.339
and they were a hell of a lot healthier
than everybody else.

00:07:15.476 --> 00:07:16.587
Yeah.

00:07:16.699 --> 00:07:20.939
So the notion that you need sugar to live

00:07:20.939 --> 00:07:24.740
or that you even need glucose to live
is disingenuous.

00:07:24.740 --> 00:07:27.084
You need a blood glucose to live,
that is true,

00:07:27.085 --> 00:07:30.019
you don't need dietary glucose to live.

00:07:30.019 --> 00:07:33.420
Because it's so important
that your liver will make it.

00:07:33.420 --> 00:07:37.860
It will make it out of amino acids
or fatty acids as needed.

00:07:37.860 --> 00:07:44.019
So glucose is essential...
it is just not essential to eat.

00:07:44.019 --> 00:07:46.620
Fructose on the other hand...

00:07:46.620 --> 00:07:52.459
there is no biochemical reaction
in any eukaryotic organism that requires it.

00:07:52.459 --> 00:07:57.180
It's completely vestigial
and when consumed in excess,

00:07:57.180 --> 00:08:00.180
because of its unique metabolism

00:08:00.180 --> 00:08:04.520
does three things that glucose does not do.

00:08:04.521 --> 00:08:08.300
One, it drives liver fat accumulation

00:08:08.300 --> 00:08:12.060
faster than virtually any other item
on the planet.

00:08:12.060 --> 00:08:16.779
Number two, it engages in the Maillard
or the agent reaction.

00:08:16.779 --> 00:08:20.620
Now glucose does it too,
but fructose does it seven times faster

00:08:20.620 --> 00:08:26.860
and it turns out there is a metabolite
of fructose that does it 250 times faster

00:08:26.860 --> 00:08:29.100
and we're working on that.

00:08:29.100 --> 00:08:34.700
And number three, fructose rather than glucose
stimulates the reward center of the brain

00:08:34.700 --> 00:08:37.500
and therefore we have the data that shows

00:08:37.500 --> 00:08:41.019
that the fructose molecule of sugar
is what it makes it addictive.

00:08:41.204 --> 00:08:45.100
So is it addictive?
Does it meet classification of addiction

00:08:45.100 --> 00:08:48.059
and therefore should it be regulated
as an addictive component?

00:08:48.238 --> 00:08:53.179
So, first of all, addictive substances are
not regulated all by themselves,

00:08:53.179 --> 00:08:56.899
otherwise Starbucks would be
out of business.

00:08:56.899 --> 00:09:00.740
And if you take my Starbucks away from me
I will kill you, okay?

00:09:00.740 --> 00:09:03.179
That's my addiction.

00:09:03.179 --> 00:09:07.172
I'm not proud of it, but at least
it's socially acceptable this week.

00:09:07.284 --> 00:09:08.697
How many have you had this morning?

00:09:08.795 --> 00:09:12.899
Three and I need my fourth.

00:09:12.899 --> 00:09:16.059
So the fact that is addictive
is not the reason for regulation.

00:09:16.059 --> 00:09:19.379
However when something is both toxic
and addictive

00:09:19.379 --> 00:09:23.059
and ubiquitous
and has detrimental effects on society

00:09:23.059 --> 00:09:26.659
then it meets the public health criteria
for regulation.

00:09:26.659 --> 00:09:29.460
In fact sugar does meet those criteria.

00:09:29.460 --> 00:09:32.500
So how is sugar addictive?

00:09:32.500 --> 00:09:37.059
In 2012 sugar was not addictive.

00:09:37.059 --> 00:09:41.179
In 2013 sugar was addictive.

00:09:41.361 --> 00:09:43.379
What's the difference?
So what changed?

00:09:43.379 --> 00:09:47.139
Sugar changed?
No, the definition changed.

00:09:47.139 --> 00:09:51.419
The American Psychiatric Association,
they are the umpire,

00:09:51.419 --> 00:09:55.100
they call the balls and strikes
on things like addiction.

00:09:55.100 --> 00:10:01.740
And they had to add gambling
as an addiction.

00:10:01.740 --> 00:10:09.620
It became very clear that behavioral addictions
went through the same CNS process,

00:10:09.620 --> 00:10:12.539
caused the same problems

00:10:12.539 --> 00:10:16.820
and had to be dealt with in the same ways
as chemical addictions.

00:10:16.820 --> 00:10:22.580
Now up till 2013 the DSM-4 said
you needed two things for addiction.

00:10:22.580 --> 00:10:25.500
You needed tolerance and withdrawal.

00:10:25.500 --> 00:10:32.139
Tolerance is the effect of these substances
on down regulation of dopamine receptors.

00:10:32.359 --> 00:10:33.989
That's why you need more and more
over time--

00:10:34.059 --> 00:10:38.820
More and more to get less and less,
that's this phenomenon called tolerance.

00:10:38.820 --> 00:10:42.419
Now the second criterion

00:10:42.419 --> 00:10:48.019
that the APA said
you had to have for addiction was withdrawal.

00:10:48.019 --> 00:10:53.539
Now turns out withdrawal, which is true
for all the chemical addictive substances,

00:10:53.539 --> 00:10:59.220
those are all effects that occur systemically
on the body, not on the brain.

00:10:59.220 --> 00:11:06.139
Caffeine withdrawal has effects on the heart,
on the vasculature, on sweat glands, etc.

00:11:06.139 --> 00:11:11.299
Opioids have effects on the G.I. tract,
have effects on the heart etc.

00:11:11.299 --> 00:11:17.460
They all have these effects that you can feel
and they cause withdrawal.

00:11:17.460 --> 00:11:21.179
Now gambling is not a chemical,

00:11:21.179 --> 00:11:26.980
gambling does not affect the body,
but it sure does affect the brain.

00:11:26.980 --> 00:11:32.779
And in order to be able to provide clinical
services under an addiction paradigm,

00:11:32.779 --> 00:11:36.779
the American Psychiatric Association
had to change the definition.

00:11:36.779 --> 00:11:42.299
So when they broke out the DSM-5 in 2013,

00:11:42.299 --> 00:11:44.820
and they do this every 20 years,

00:11:44.820 --> 00:11:48.220
now the definition could be
tolerance and withdrawal

00:11:48.220 --> 00:11:51.726
or tolerance and dependence.

00:11:51.727 --> 00:11:55.379
There is nine criteria for dependence,
we don't have time for each one...

00:11:55.379 --> 00:11:58.059
You can look them up, they're online.

00:11:58.059 --> 00:12:01.899
And gambling meets all of them,
gaming disorder meets all of them,

00:12:01.899 --> 00:12:05.569
social media meets all of them,
shopping meets all of them,

00:12:05.570 --> 00:12:09.940
pornography meets all of them and
guess what? Sugar meets all of them too.

00:12:09.940 --> 00:12:14.980
So we have substance addictions and
we also have behavioral addictions.

00:12:14.980 --> 00:12:21.379
And sugar happens to be a substance that
induces both tolerance and dependence.

00:12:21.379 --> 00:12:24.779
Anyone who says,
"Oh, I have a horrible sweet tooth"...

00:12:24.779 --> 00:12:26.577
They're sugar addict.

00:12:26.716 --> 00:12:31.299
But is knowing that enough to change
public policy or to change people?

00:12:31.299 --> 00:12:34.659
Certainly not enough to change
people's activities on their own

00:12:34.659 --> 00:12:36.580
and change their decisions.

00:12:36.580 --> 00:12:38.940
So what else has to be in place for us

00:12:38.940 --> 00:12:42.100
to be able to say, "This is a public health
crisis that we need intervene upon?"

00:12:42.276 --> 00:12:45.059
We have two templates to look at.

00:12:45.059 --> 00:12:47.340
Tobacco and alcohol.

00:12:47.340 --> 00:12:50.740
So for years smoking was a liberty interest.

00:12:50.740 --> 00:12:53.580
You had a liberty interest to smoke.

00:12:53.580 --> 00:12:57.379
Boreali v. Axelrod, a famous New York State
Supreme Court case

00:12:57.379 --> 00:13:01.100
said you have a liberty interest to smoke
and you know what?

00:13:01.100 --> 00:13:04.379
The New York state legislature
understanding what the problem was

00:13:04.379 --> 00:13:08.860
and understanding that
the tobacco industry was disingenuous

00:13:08.860 --> 00:13:14.940
started passing laws that said you can't
smoke in bars, you can't smoke in atria,

00:13:14.940 --> 00:13:18.379
you can't smoke in restaurants,
you can't smoke in schools,

00:13:18.379 --> 00:13:21.216
you can't smoke in hospitals

00:13:21.217 --> 00:13:27.460
and now you can't even smoke in your car
if there's a kid in it.

00:13:27.460 --> 00:13:31.379
And the thing is
when it first started coming out

00:13:31.379 --> 00:13:33.379
people were yelling,
"Nanny state, nanny state".

00:13:33.379 --> 00:13:35.179
They're not doing that anymore.

00:13:35.359 --> 00:13:38.784
Part of that though is because of,
"I'm smoking here, I'm going to affect you".

00:13:38.899 --> 00:13:39.957
Exactly.

00:13:40.059 --> 00:13:42.579
I'm drinking my Coca-Cola here,
that's not going to affect you.

00:13:42.659 --> 00:13:44.779
-Oh, yes it is.
-How?

00:13:45.115 --> 00:13:46.740
Monetarily.

00:13:46.740 --> 00:13:49.940
Because if I have to go
to the emergency room

00:13:49.940 --> 00:13:54.220
I won't be able to get in
because there will be gurneys filled

00:13:54.220 --> 00:13:59.379
with people with sugar beverage
associated heart disease

00:13:59.379 --> 00:14:03.980
waiting for their coronary bypasses
or their TPA.

00:14:03.980 --> 00:14:06.580
And there won't be any money
in the system

00:14:06.580 --> 00:14:10.460
for me to be able to access
that health care in the first place.

00:14:10.460 --> 00:14:14.899
Medicare will be broke by the year 2026,
Social Security will be broke by 2034

00:14:14.899 --> 00:14:17.700
because of this.

00:14:17.700 --> 00:14:22.019
So while it is not an assault on your person

00:14:22.019 --> 00:14:25.980
like tobacco is or like alcohol is
in terms of car accidents,

00:14:25.980 --> 00:14:30.779
it is an assault on your person
in terms of your economy.

00:14:30.779 --> 00:14:34.460
Now you could argue
that's not the same

00:14:34.460 --> 00:14:38.580
but the fact of the matter is
we still have to deal with it the same.

00:14:38.799 --> 00:14:41.620
Right, our society is not good
at seeing that next step.

00:14:41.620 --> 00:14:43.820
We're very good at seeing
the immediate--

00:14:44.001 --> 00:14:47.500
And the reason is
because we're all addicted.

00:14:47.500 --> 00:14:52.100
Addiction is about now
and happiness is about the future.

00:14:52.100 --> 00:14:57.340
It's about basically making life better
for later.

00:14:57.340 --> 00:15:02.179
We are into reward,
we are not into happiness,

00:15:02.179 --> 00:15:07.659
we are into instant gratification,
we are not into delayed gratification.

00:15:07.659 --> 00:15:11.139
Now, we doctors, know everything about
delayed gratification,

00:15:11.139 --> 00:15:14.299
because we went through med school,
residency, fellowship, etc.

00:15:14.299 --> 00:15:18.860
and we delayed, you know,
being able to see any money

00:15:18.860 --> 00:15:24.820
or, you know, even patient care on our own
for 10, 15 sometimes even 20 years.

00:15:24.820 --> 00:15:27.899
We know everything there is to know
about delayed gratification.

00:15:27.899 --> 00:15:30.500
The fact of the matter is
the American public does not.

00:15:30.676 --> 00:15:33.659
And a lot of that has to do with industry

00:15:33.659 --> 00:15:37.580
and what has been put in front of us
in terms of choices we can make.

00:15:37.580 --> 00:15:42.419
And we are in an on-demand society,
we are in an instant gratification society

00:15:42.419 --> 00:15:44.940
and that's not something
that's going to be easy to fix.

00:15:45.193 --> 00:15:48.500
We are a dopamine society...
that is what it is.

00:15:48.500 --> 00:15:51.940
It is dopamine, call it what it is.

00:15:51.940 --> 00:15:55.580
So this is why I wrote this book,
&lt;i&gt;The Hacking of the American Mind&lt;/i&gt;;

00:15:55.580 --> 00:16:01.597
is to differentiate these two phenomena,
one called pleasure, one called happiness.

00:16:01.598 --> 00:16:06.940
Washington DC, Las Vegas,
Madison Avenue, Wall Street, Silicon Valley

00:16:06.940 --> 00:16:11.779
have confused and conflated
these two terms on purpose.

00:16:11.779 --> 00:16:15.700
Because then they can "sell" you happiness.

00:16:15.700 --> 00:16:18.500
